    <br>
   It was late afternoon and, judging by the surroundings, I was still some distance from the city.  Though it was still bright, many of the colorful birds had already sought their nests.  Here and there swarms of night insects began to stir, lifting themselves under the leaves of bushesby the road.  The shadows of the trees had grown long, and, judging by the shadows, it was nearing time to stop and make camp, as I was in no hurry to make my destination.  <br>
<br>
  I wondered if it was still practical to continue my journey, the sun would soon be down, and the night was not without it's dangers, particularly to a man on foot.  It is at night that the many Trollocs that seem to have found their way to this part of the world make their presence known, not to mention the wolves, and Thieves.<br>
<br>
  I came to the decision that I would withdraw from the road, wrap myself in my cloak, and spend the night in the shelter of some rocks, or perhaps crawl into the tangle of some thorn bushes, where one might sleep in relative security.  Now that I was considering discontinuing my journey, I suddenly became acutely aware that I was both hungry and thirsty.  I reached into my leather pack and fished out a skin of water, and a piece of dried meat, it would have to do for now.<br>
<br>
 I had scarcely stepped from the road when, coming down the road, each step carefully measured and solid, I saw a wide, hunched figure, bending under a gigantic bundle of sticks, strapped to his back by two cords which he held twisted in his fists in front of his body.  His load was probably to fuel the fires of his home.  The weight the man was carrying was quite staggering, and would have staggered most large men, this man was very strong. <br>
<br>
 The man approached more closely.  His eyes were almost covered with a white, shaggy, mess of hair, with twigs and leaves entangled in it.  The whiskers had been scraped from his face, probably by the blade of the broad double-headed wood ax bound on top of the bundle.  He wore a short tattered sleeveless robe, which had a leather back and shoulder area, on his feet he wore heavy leather boots, worn down and looked ready to fall apart.<br>
<br>
 I stepped into the road before him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hello,&quot; I said lifting my hand in greeting.<br>
<br>
The shaggy creature, broad, powerful, monstrous in appearance, stood before me, his feet planted firmly on the road.  His head lifted, it's wide narrow eyes, pale like water, regarded me through the brush of hair that almost concealed them.<br>
<br>
In spite of his slow reaction to my presence, his deliberate and patient movements, I gathered that he was surprised.  he had apparantly not expected to meet anyone on this road.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hello,&quot; he said, his voice thick, almost less that human.  I sensed that he was considering how quickly he could get to the ax bound across the bundle.<br>
<br>
&quot;I mean you no harm,&quot; I said.<br>
<br>
&quot;What do you want?&quot; asked the man, who must now have noticed the sword over my shoulder, and probably considered me an thief.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am not an outlaw,&quot; I said.  He obviously didn't believe me.  &quot;I am hungry,&quot; I said &quot;I have very little food on me, and have barely eaten all day.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I too am hungry,&quot; he said, &quot;and have had nothing to eat in many hours.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Is your home near?&quot; I asked.  I knew it would be from the time of day at which I had encountered him.  The sun usually dictates the schedules of most country dwellers.<br>
<br>
&quot;No&quot; he said.<br>
<br>
&quot;I mean you no harm, I have a little money and can pay you for the food.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;An outlaw takes what he wishes,&quot; said the man.  He regarded me, and I thought I saw the trace of a smile cracked through the stubbled leather of his broad face.  &quot;I have no daughter, I have no silver, and no goods.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Then I wish you prosperity,&quot; I laughed, &quot;and will be on my way.&quot;  I passed him and continued down the road.  I had moved but a few steps when his voice arrested me.  It was hard to understand the words, for his voice was rough, and it sounded as though he did not use it often.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have peas and turnips, garlic and onions in my home&quot; said the man, his bundle like a giant hump on his back.<br>
<br>
&quot;The creator himself could not ask for more.&quot;  I said to the man.<br>
<br>
&quot;then friend,&quot; said the man, issuing me an invitation to dine with him, &quot;share my table.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I am honored&quot; I said, and I was.<br>
<br>
