<br>
   Was I not Mandinga Bedoa of Tar Valon?  Was there not such a city?  Each sign I saw said there was one.  Yet why did the road look untraveled?  Why had Ruon the stick carrier acted as he had?  I stopped and looked at the stars above me, finally the clouds had cleared and they and the moon could be seen.  The sky above me was alive with the brilliant points of light, some flickering, some white, some yellow, but all breathtaking, if not for my determination to move on, I could have found a safe spot to lie and look at the stars till morning.<br>
<br>
  I prepared to set forth on my journey again, grateful now that the moon might guide my path on this perilous road.  I asked mysef, in a sane moment, if I should not seek shelter, and I knew that I should, but I could not, because questions burned within me that I could not dare to answer.  Only the evidence of my eyes and ears could allay my fears, my bewilderment.  I sought a truth I did not know, but I knew I must discover, and it lay at the end of this road.<br>
<br>
  I caught a strange, unpleasant scent, much like that of an unclean animal, but stronger.  In that instant every sense was alert.  I froze, and almost animal response.  I was silent, not moving, seeking the shelter of stillness and immobility.  My head turned imperceptibly as I scanned the rocks and bushes about the road.  I thought I heard a light sniffling, a grunt, a small doglike whine, then nothing.<br>
<br>
  It to had frozen, probably sensing my presence.  Most likely it was a trolloc, hopefully one on it's own, I guessed it had not been hunting me, or I would not likely to have smelled it.  It would have approached me from upwind, if it had any sense of a hunter that is.  I stood still for a good 2 to 3 minutes, then I saw, tall, a man beast, lumber across the road, it's face with a doglike snout.<br>
<br>
  I breathed a sigh of relief, it was alone, so not much of a danger, it's attack, if it should detect my presence, would be little more than a nuisance, probably a clumsy noisy charge.  It staggered into the darkness, not seeing me on the road, and continued on to whereever it was going.  Strange to see a Trolloc so close to city.<br>
<br>
  Black, scudding clouds again obscured the moon, and the wind began to rise.  I could see the shadows of tall trees bending against the darkness of the night, their leaves lifting and rustling on the long branches.  I smelled rain in the air.  In the far distance there was a sudden flash of lightning, and the sound of remote thunder reached me some seconds later.<br>
<br>
  As I hurried on, I became more apprehensive.  By now it seemed to me that I should be able to see the lights of the tall cylinder of the White Tower.  The wind gathered force, seeming to tear at the trees.<br>
<br>
  In a flash of light I spied a wooden sign and eagerly rushed to it.  In the mounting of the wind and darkness I traced the numbering on the wood.  It was true.  I should now be able to see the lights of Tar Valon, Yet I could see nothing.  The city must be in darkness.<br>
<br>
  Why were the lanterns not hung on the bridges, why were the lamps of a hundred colors and flames no lit in the buildings of the city,.  Why was it in darkness, why?<br>
<br>
  I stood by the sign, trying to understand.  I was confused, uncertain.  Now that I had not seen the lights of Tar Valon, as I would have expected, it struck me more forcibly that I had not even seen the lights of country cooking fires glowing in the terain surrounding the city, or the torches of guards patrolling the roads around the city.<br>
<br>
  A monstrous chain of lightning exploded in the night about me, deafening me with the shock and roar of it's thunder, splitting the darkness in violent fragments, breaking it to pieces like a clay bowl struck with a hammer of fire, and with the lightning, the storm descended, fierce cold torrents of icy rain whipped by the wind.<br>
